      "title": "See also"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "For developers of NumPy: do not instantiate this at the module level.\nThe initial calculation of these parameters is expensive and negatively\nimpacts import times.  These objects are cached, so calling "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "finfo()"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "\nrepeatedly inside your functions is not a problem."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Note that "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "smallest_normal"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is not actually the smallest positive\nrepresentable value in a NumPy floating point type. As in the IEEE-754\nstandard "
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "[1]_"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", NumPy floating point types make use of subnormal numbers to\nfill the gap between 0 and "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "smallest_normal"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ". However, subnormal numbers\nmay have significantly reduced precision "
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "[2]_"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "This function can also be used for complex data types as well. If used,\nthe output will be the same as the corresponding real float type\n(e.g. we.finfo(we.csingle) is the same as we.finfo(we.single)).\nHowever, the output is true for the real and imaginary components."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "1\n\nIEEE Standard for Floating-Point Arithmetic, IEEE Std 754-2008,\npp.1-70, 2008, https://doi.org/10.1109/IEEESTD.2008.4610935",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "2\n\nWikipedia, \"Denormal Numbers\",\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denormal_number",
